rounds.response:
Let's size up the situation:

My current stock and unit values  
- Wheat: 12 × 5 = 60  
- Wood: 10 × 12 = 120  
- Sheep: 22 × 14 = 308  
- Brick: 10 × 21 = 210  
- Ore : 23 × 39 = 897  
Total value = 1 595

Key observations  
1. Ore ($39/ea) is by far my most valuable resource; I should add more rather than give it away.  
2. Wheat and Wood are my cheapest resources ($5 and $12).  
3. I have 22 Sheep and 10 Brick—both well above the other bank counts—which makes both relatively expendable if I get fair value.

The last offer I received: 5 Wheat (worth 25) + 3 Wood (worth 36) ⇆ 2 Ore (worth 78). Net I would gain 78 – 61 = 17 value. It is a small net gain, but it also means recovering Ore at a poor rate (≈$30 per Ore when new Ore would otherwise cost me ≈$39 cash value). That is not attractive enough. [Deny]

My new counter-proposal: I want to thin out some Sheep while landing more Ore/Brick. A realistic high-value offer based on relative scarcity is to offer 4 Sheep ($56 value) for 1 Ore ($39) + 1 Brick ($21). I lose 4 of my 22 low-value Sheep and gain two of the scarcer high-value materials. Net value change = +$4 for me. It’s polite while still profitable.

[Offer: 4 Sheep -> 1 Ore, 1 Brick]

The last offer by Player-0 is way worse than market value.  
One Brick (value 21) for two Sheep (value 28 total) would make me **lose 7 value**.  
Therefore it is an easy reject.

Now it is my turn (Turn 10).  
My current value totals 168 points, but I am nowhere near any “victory” threshold, and Player-0 has shown he will not give Ore at a reasonable price.  
I hold 23 Ore (value 39 each), the most valuable resource, so selling even one single Ore at the price everyone keeps bidding (5–6 value worth of goods for one 39-value Ore) is a huge loss.  
Thus there is no conceivable offer I can profitably make at this swing.  
Instead, I will simply stay flat.

[Deny]
